First understand why this matters.

Companies like Amazon or Microsoft don’t just check if your code works. They check how efficient it is. Two students may solve the same problem — the one with the faster algorithm gets the job.

That’s where Big-O time complexity comes in.

What Big-O Actually Means

Big-O tells how fast your program grows when input grows.

Example 1
If a program checks 10 numbers, it may take 10 steps.
If it checks 1000 numbers, it may take 1000 steps.

Example 2
Another program might compare every number with every other number.
For 10 numbers → 100 operations
For 1000 numbers → 1,000,000 operations

Second program becomes extremely slow.

The Most Important Complexities
1. O(1) – Constant Time

Execution time never changes.

Example 1

int x = arr[5];

Example 2

return arr[0];

No matter if array has 10 elements or 1 million, time is same.

2. O(n) – Linear Time

Program runs once for each element.

Example 1

for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
   System.out.println(arr[i]);
}

Example 2
Finding largest number in array.

You must check every element once.

3. O(n²) – Quadratic Time

Nested loops. Very slow when data grows.

Example 1

for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
   for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
      System.out.println(arr[i] + arr[j]);
   }
}

Example 2
Bubble sort algorithm.

If n = 1000, operations ≈ 1,000,000.

Why This Matters in Interviews

Example problem: Find duplicate in array

Student A solution
Two loops → O(n²)

Student B solution
Using HashSet → O(n)

Both correct.
Company chooses Student B.

